    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each of metric/trace/log files: group records by component (cmdb_id) and KPI name (kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv). For each group compute: count, mean, min, max, global P95 and global P5 of the 'value' column. Return a compact table (limit to top 50 rows) listing: source_file, cmdb_id, kpi_name (or trace_name/log_name), count, mean, min, max, p95, p5. Also return the list of unique cmdb_id values found across all files and the number of distinct KPI names per component (compact). Do not filter by incident window in this step; compute thresholds from the full available series." }

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global thresholds and anomaly counts for the five candidate services and found many anomalies, but noted a major confounder: many KPIs have global P95 == global P5 == 0.0 which inflates anomaly counts (points equal to 0 are counted as both high and low). All services show earliest anomaly around 2024-01-22T17:09:00+00:00. To localize the root cause we must ignore KPIs with equal/zero thresholds and focus on KPIs with meaningful (global_p95 > global_p5) thresholds and significant breaches inside the incident window. Those KPIs will indicate real resource or latency faults that can be traced and correlated with logs/traces. Next we should list the candidate-component KPIs whose global thresholds are non-degenerate and rank them by meaningful anomaly severity (high-anomaly count and how much the window max exceeds the global P95). This will narrow the candidate faulty KPIs/services for trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) use metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv results already loaded. From the previously-computed per-component-KPI global thresholds and the incident-window filtered values, select only rows where global_p95 > global_p5 (i.e., non-degenerate thresholds). For those rows compute an additional field breach_ratio defined as:\n - if global_p95 > 0: (max_value_in_window - global_p95) / global_p95\n - else: set breach_ratio = NaN\nReturn the top 20 rows sorted by anomalies_high_count desc then breach_ratio desc. Include columns: source_file, cmdb_id, kpi_name (or trace_name/log_name), global_p95, global_p5, count_in_window, anomalies_high_count, earliest_high_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, breaches_ratio (as defined). Also return a compact per-component short list (one row per candidate) showing the top 3 KPI names by breach_ratio for that component (kpi_name and breach_ratio). Limit outputs to at most 20 rows for the first table and 5 rows (one per component) for the second summary."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, anomaly detection, and initial fault identification. Key findings: (1) a short but high-relative trace latency spike involving ts-order-service and its calls to ts-inside-payment-service (notably trace.from_ts-inside-payment-service.duration_p95 with breach_ratio > 1.0 at ~17:15 UTC), and (2) a 2-minute large absolute disk I/O spike on ts-train-service at ~17:09–17:10 UTC (breach_ratio ≈ 0.56). Many other smaller/single-minute anomalies cluster near ~17:09 UTC. Logs and error_logs did not show error_count > 0 or error messages for the five candidate services in the window, so we must rely on metrics and traces to localize the root cause.

What remains ambiguous: both ts-order-related trace spikes and ts-train disk I/O spikes are strong candidates. Per the localization rules, when multiple service-level faults exist we should pick the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chain. Therefore we need focused trace-call-chain evidence showing call relationships between the candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) and which of them appears as the downstream faulty node in anomalous traces. The next step is to extract trace rows within the incident window that explicitly reference these candidate services as peers (trace.from_<svc> or trace.to_<svc>), mark which of those trace rows are anomalous relative to their global P95, and aggregate anomalies per (cmdb_id, direction, peer_service) so we can infer call directions and identify the last-downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to the incident window (timestamps between '2024-01-22 17:06:32 UTC' and '2024-01-22 17:36:32 UTC'). For each trace component-KPI compute global_p95 using the full trace.csv series (do NOT compute thresholds from the window). Parse trace_name to extract direction and peer_service: if trace_name contains 'from_<svc>' extract '<svc>' and set direction='from'; if contains 'to_<svc>' extract '<svc>' and set direction='to'; else peer_service=NULL and direction='other'.

Then restrict to rows where peer_service is one of: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service, or where cmdb_id is one of these five. Mark high_anomaly if value >= global_p95. Aggregate by cmdb_id, direction, peer_service to compute: count_in_window, anomalies_high_count, earliest_high_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, global_p95. Return up to 50 aggregated rows sorted by anomalies_high_count desc then max_value_in_window desc. Also return up to 50 raw trace rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, direction, peer_service, high_anomaly) that reference any of these five services (either as cmdb_id or peer) to inspect call chains and timestamps." }

Based on the metric and trace analysis (notably a sustained diskio spike on ts-train-service at ~17:09 UTC and correlated trace anomalies), the most likely root cause is a disk I/O issue on ts-train-service.

